For example, (-1, 1, 6) and (-1, 6, 1) and (1, -1, 6) etc., all 6 permutations. Each of these gives the same (a, b) as the set { -1, 1, 6 }, which is (-6, -1). Similarly, permutations of (-1, 2, 3) all give the same (a, b) as the set { -1, 2, 3 }, which is (-4, 1). Similarly for the others. Similarly, for the three-negative-number triplet (-1, -2, -3): Permutations of this will all give the same (a, b) as the set { -1, -2, -3 }, which is (6, 11). Therefore, each multiset corresponds to 6 ordered triples, but all 6 result in the same (a, b). Therefore, the total number of distinct (a, b) pairs is 5. But wait, hold on. Let's check if there's any other triplet that we missed. For example, is there a triplet with three negative numbers but different absolute values? For example, (-1, -2, -3) is the only triplet with three negative numbers. Because to have three negative numbers with product -6, their absolute values must multiply to 6, and distinct. The only triplet of distinct positive integers multiplying to 6 is (1, 2, 3). Therefore, the three-negative-number triplet is unique. So that's one.
